        <h2 id="examples">Real Google Maps marketing examples</h2>

        <h3>Example 1 — New restaurant launch</h3>
        <p>A new Thai restaurant in Austin completes their GBP with 30+ photos, a full menu, accurate hours, and specific category tags. They ask every diner for a review with a table tent card. After 60 days and 80 reviews averaging 4.6 stars, they consistently appear in the top 3 map results for "Thai food near me" within a 5-mile radius — without spending a dollar on ads.</p>

        <h3>Example 2 — Service business expanding reach</h3>
        <p>A roofing company publishes GBP posts weekly: project photos, seasonal tips ("roof inspection before monsoon season"), and limited-time offers. Combined with location-specific content on their website targeting nearby cities, their Google Maps visibility expands from a 3-mile radius to a 10-mile radius within 4 months.</p>

        <h3>Example 3 — Recovery from GBP suspension</h3>
        <p>A law firm's GBP is suspended after a competitor reports it for a suspected policy violation. Without a verified listing, they disappear entirely from Maps. They submit a reinstatement request with documentation, restore the profile within 3 weeks, and rebuild their review count over the following 60 days. Lesson: GBP is infrastructure, not decoration.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Google Maps marketing vs Google Ads — which to use?</h2>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Google Maps Marketing (Organic)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>No cost per click — sustainable long-term visibility</li>
              <li>Higher trust — users click organic map results more</li>
              <li>Compounds over time as reviews and signals accumulate</li>
              <li>Works 24/7 without budget management</li>
              <li>Essential for businesses with limited ad budgets</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Local Search Ads (Paid)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Instant visibility — no waiting for optimization</li>
              <li>Precise geo-targeting and radius control</li>
              <li>Stops working the moment budget runs out</li>
              <li>Cost-per-click in competitive local markets: $5-$50+</li>
              <li>Best as a short-term supplement, not a long-term strategy</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 Google Maps marketing best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Complete your GBP to 100%.</strong> Every missing field is a ranking signal you're leaving on the table. Add all services, products, attributes, and a detailed business description with natural keyword usage.</li>
          <li><strong>Post to GBP weekly.</strong> Fresh posts signal an active business. Include images in every post — GBPs with photos receive 35% more clicks than those without (Google, 2023).</li>
          <li><strong>Build a review acquisition system.</strong> Ask at the point of peak satisfaction — right after a service is completed, not a week later. A QR code linking to your Google review page reduces friction significantly.</li>
          <li><strong>Respond to every review.</strong> Google has confirmed that responding to reviews is a ranking factor. Thank positive reviewers. Address negative ones professionally and specifically.</li>
          <li><strong>Audit NAP consistency quarterly.</strong> Run a citation audit using BrightLocal or Moz Local. Fix discrepancies in business name, address format, and phone number across all directories.</li>
          <li><strong>Add photos systematically.</strong> Upload interior, exterior, product, team, and before/after photos. Update monthly. Google Maps surfaces businesses with recent, diverse photo sets more frequently.</li>
          <li><strong>Create location-specific website content.</strong> City pages, neighborhood guides, and local project showcases all strengthen the website signals that reinforce your GBP's local relevance.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — keyword stuffing your business name</div>
          <p>Adding extra keywords to your GBP business name field (e.g., "Joe's Plumbing - Best Plumber Austin Texas") is a Google policy violation that can result in GBP suspension. Use your exact legal business name. Keyword relevance comes from categories, services, and posts — not from the name field.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common Google Maps marketing mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Leaving GBP fields incomplete.</strong> Incomplete profiles lose to completed ones at every tier of competition.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring review responses.</strong> Unanswered negative reviews damage star ratings and signal low engagement to Google.</li>
          <li><strong>Inconsistent NAP data.</strong> "St." on one directory and "Street" on another creates citation confusion that suppresses rankings.</li>
          <li><strong>Posting only promotional content.</strong> GBP posts that mix educational tips, project photos, and offers outperform purely promotional posts.</li>
          <li><strong>Using the wrong primary category.</strong> Your primary category is the single strongest relevance signal in your GBP. Choose the most specific accurate category available.</li>
          <li><strong>Treating GBP as a one-time setup.</strong> Maps rankings decay without active maintenance. Competitors who post and earn reviews consistently will eventually overtake dormant profiles.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
